defaultWritten evidence from the Law Commission (SLC0060)
default1.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Law 
defaultCommission and Scottish Law Commission recently completed a review of the legal framework governing level crossings. We published a report on 25 September 2013, together with a draft Bill and draft health and safety Regulations. We also published an analys
defaultis of consultation responses and an economic impact assessment.
default 
default1.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHere we set out the background to this project, our major findings and a summary of our proposals. 
defaultThe full report and supporting documents may be found at: 
defaulthttp://lawcommission.justice.gov.uk/publications/level-crossings.htm
default.
default 
default1.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Law Commissions’ work is most relevant to the Transport Select Committee’s question: h
defaultow should the legislation governing level crossings be updated? 
default1.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe were asked by the Department for Transport and the Office of Rail Regulation to take on this project as part of our 10th Programme of law reform in 2008. The ORR had carried ou
defaultt a consultation in which stakeholders, including Network Rail and highways authorities, had strongly supported a review of the legislation on level crossings because the law is outdated, unclear, difficult to access and to understand. 
default1.5
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA consultation pape
defaultr was published in July 2010 and we consulted for four months, including meetings with a wide range of stakeholders and site visits to a variety of mainline and heritage railways and tramways. Policy continued to develop as a result of consultation. Both s
defaultets of Commissioners then approved the policy we had developed and gave permission to instruct Parliamentary counsel. Counsel drafted a Bill and Regulations under the Health and Safety at Work etc Act 1974. A final report was approved by both Commissions i
defaultn the summer of 2013 and the report, draft Bill, draft Regulations, analysis of consultation responses and impact assessment were published in September 2013. 
default1.6
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis project took longer than we expected for several reasons. The scale of the project was huge
default and wide-ranging, as is apparent from the size of the report. It involved intricate consideration of highway law and railway law, as well as land law, planning law, compulsory purchase, health and safety, criminal law and regulatory theory. The law in 
defaultSco
defaulttland
default is fundamentally different from that in 
defaultEngland
default and 
defaultWales
default in some places, for example in relation to rights of way. The project required close collaboration between the two Law Commissions. Each step of the project was peer-reviewed by both Commissio
defaultns within different timetables. We also co-operated closely with a wide range of stakeholders. The end result was a 300-page report, containing over 100 recommendations. 
default1.7
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe terms of reference of the project were:
default“To review the law relating to leve
defaultl crossings, and make recommendations, with a view to providing a modern regulatory framework for level crossings and to simplify and modernise that law.”
default1.8
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe aims of the project were
default: 
default1.9
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere is no reference in the terms of reference to safety. While a good regulatory system will facilitate safety improvements, we do not claim that our recommendations will directly, of them
defaultselves, improve safety.
default 
default1.10
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOur findings and recommendations fall into three broad areas: safety and convenience; closure of level crossings and rights of way. Most of our recommendations are given effect in the draft Level Crossings Bill and 
defaultdraft Level Crossings Plans Regulations. In addition, there are some areas which we investigated, but did not make significant recommendations for law reform. These are considered in the final Part of the report and include: criminal offences; signs; plann
defaulting law; barrow crossings and open crossings; and finally, the design of level crossings.
default 
default1.11
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe summarise our recommendations briefly here:  
defaultFindingsdefault1.12
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe found that the legislation governing level crossings is complex 
defaultand antiquated including
default: 
default 
default1.13
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIt is not always easy to know which law is still in force and which takes precedence. 
default1.14
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn addition, we found that the current procedures for changing protective arrangements at level crossings under level crossing orders is cum
defaultbersome and tends to lead to arrangements (barriers, lights and so on) remaining in place even when they are no longer the most suitable solution. This can compromise the convenience and efficiency of both the road and rail networks and inconvenience has a
default close relationship to safety. 
default1.15
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe found that effective management of level crossings, and the efficiency of road and rail at the crossing, can be significantly affected by good (or poor) co-operation between the railway operator and the highway authority 
defaultor private beneficiary of the crossing. 
default1.16
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe also found that the convenience of the railway tends to take precedence as railway operators are under no obligation to consider the convenience of non-rail users when deciding what arrangements are put in place.
default 
default1.17
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe considered the enforcing authorities and found that there is a lack of clarity as to when ORR is responsible for enforcement following road-rail incursions. This goes beyond level crossings and applies to railways more generally. 
defaultRecommendationsdefault1.18
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe c
defaultoncluded that the regulation of level crossings could be simplified by removing other sources of regulation and leaving level crossings to be governed by the Health and Safety at Work etc Act 1974, which already applies to the railways and to workplaces in
default general. 
default1.19
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe considered whether decisions should be restricted to the Secretary of State, as health and safety are reserved matters, but concluded that it was more appropriate for decisions about individual level crossings to be made at a more local level
default, balancing the local powers in respect of highways and roads with national oversight of safety. So we recommended that the decisions described below should be made by the Secretary of State in relation to 
defaultEngland
default, Scottish Ministers in relation to 
defaultScotlan
defaultd
default and Welsh Ministers in relation to 
defaultWales
default. 
