default1.27
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultLevel crossings are difficult to close under the current law.
default 
default1.28
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA level crossing always poses a ri
defaultsk to safety and can be inconvenient to both road and rail as well. Network Rail and ORR are committed to closing level crossings where possible, but this must be balanced against the needs of communities in maintaining access across the railway. 
default1.29
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe recommend a new, more streamlined system for deciding whether it is in the public interest to close a level crossing with or without a replacement. 
default1.30
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe decision would be made by the Secretary of State, Scottish or Welsh Ministers who would be r
defaultequired to consider all relevant issues
default and decide whether the scheme as a whole was in the public interest. That would include:  
default(1)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultthe safety of the public
default 
default(2)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultthe convenience of the public
default(3)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultthe efficiency of the transport network (including the network of 
defaultpublic paths)
default(4)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultthe cost of maintaining the crossing
default(5)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultthe need for the crossing and its significance for the local community (including the protection of heritage)
default(6)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultthe costs and environmental impact of any works needed to replace the crossing or upgrade other
default crossings. 
default1.31
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe recommend a combined consent procedure, which provides for: the closure of the level crossing; the extinguishment of the rights of way across the railway; compensation; the diversion of any right of way; planning permission or other permiss
defaultions required to build any replacement bridge or underpass; compulsory purchase powers and compensation for compulsory purchase. 
default1.32
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA closure decision would be subject to challenge to the High Court by way of statutory judicial review. 
default1.33
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn addition, we have 
defaultrecommended health and safety regulations to enable highway authorities to be required to place signs, or paint lines or take other necessary action on the highway near a level crossing. 
default1.34
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultLastly, there are area
defaults of land law and the law of rights of way which are not entirely clear in relation to level crossings. Some level crossings were created by the grant of an easement (or servitude in Scotland) across the railway, others were created by 
defaultmodel clauses from t
defaulthe Railway Clauses Consolidation Act 1845
default in 
defaulta special Act, and this has led to some confusion over how far the law of easements applies to these crossings. 
